Welfare aids needy people and families. Welfare examples: Cash assistance: Programs that provide low-income people money for food, shelter, and clothes. Food vouchers or food stamps for low-income families and individuals. Housing assistance: Programs that help low-income families afford secure and stable housing using financial aid or vouchers. Health care: Medicaid and Medicare for low-income households. Daycare assistance: Programs that help low-income families pay for childcare so parents may work or attend school. Education assistance: Pell Grants and student loans for low-income students and families. Job training and employment assistance for low-income people: These are just a few examples; welfare laws and programs may vary by nation or location and be delivered by the government, non-profits, or private institutions. Welfare helps families satisfy their fundamental necessities and enhance their well-being. 